@flexiarg war-machine/inhabitation-threshold
@title Inhabitation Threshold

! conclusion: Infrastructure that is 90% built and 0% inhabited produces zero value; the last 10% that reduces entry friction is what creates the value because it crosses the inhabitation threshold.

  + CONTEXT:
    The evidence pipeline, pattern retrieval, browser surfaces, and HUD were all built before the session that finally fixed the entry ceremony. Once the friction bugs were removed, the already-built infrastructure became inhabited immediately.

  + IF:
    A stack surface is largely built but still too awkward, brittle, or ritual-heavy to enter during ordinary work.

  + HOWEVER:
    Prerequisite build-out is real, and inhabitation alone can also become a trap if it never deposits externally. The failure mode here is not building, but infrastructure that exists without being used.

  + THEN:
    Treat entry friction as severity-critical. Measure inhabitation as a first-class metric and prioritise the fixes that let ordinary work actually pass through the surface.

  + BECAUSE:
    The war machine exists only when it is inhabited. No new capability was required once the entry bugs were fixed; the same infrastructure started producing evidence as soon as the threshold was crossed.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Audit every major surface for the exact bug or ritual that still blocks ordinary entry, and fix those before adding new capability.]
